# Work on PRD

Work through a PRD's issues in dependency order. Default execution model: one integration feature branch, with parallel git worktrees for independent AFK issues, merged back and cleaned up at the end.

## Input

The user provides a project slug or path (e.g., `auth` or `{{.plans_dir}}auth/`).

If none provided, ask: "Which PRD should I work on? (project slug or path)"

## Workflow states

```
{{join " → " .workflow_states}}
```

## Process

### 1. Read the PRD and issues

Read `{{.plans_dir}}{slug}/prd.yaml` and all files in `{{.plans_dir}}{slug}/issues/`.

If no issue files exist, tell the user: "This PRD has no implementation issues. Run `/bender-prd-to-issues` first."

### 2. Set up the integration branch

All work for this PRD lands on **one** feature branch. Never commit issue work directly to the default branch.

- branch: `<user>/<project-slug>` (e.g., `jason/auth`)
- create off the repo's default branch (`main` or `master`) if missing; otherwise reuse
- per-issue branches root here and merge back here
- a single combined PR is opened from this branch at the end

### 3. Discover the ready batch

Use `{{.commands.next}} {slug}` as the source of truth for what to pick up. It returns JSON:

- `issue` — the chosen issue, or `null` if no candidate is ready
- `reason` — why it was picked (status, priority, flags)
- `was_blocked` — true when the issue had `status: blocked` but its blockers are now done|canceled. Set status to `todo` before starting.
- `requires_human` — true when only HITL candidates remain. Surface to the user instead of auto-starting.
- `all_done` — true when every issue is `done` or `canceled`. Skip to §6.
- `blocked_count` — count of issues still truly blocked (informational).
- `skipped[]` — every issue not chosen, each with a one-line reason.

Trust the resolver's ordering — never re-derive it from YAML.

To assemble a **parallel batch**: call `{{.commands.next}} {slug}` to confirm at least one ready candidate, then enumerate every other ready issue by reading the YAML files (status `todo` or stale-blocked, all `blocked_by` in done|canceled, AFK only). The resolver picks one at a time; the batch is the set we'll dispatch concurrently.

### 4. Dispatch the batch

An issue is **parallelizable** when:

- AFK (not HITL)
- not flagged `headed: true` (browser sessions don't parallelize cleanly)
- its step targets do not overlap another batched issue's targets (best-effort scan of `target` fields — when in doubt, sequence them)

#### Parallel worktrees (2+ parallelizable issues)

For each parallelizable issue, prepare a worktree off the integration branch:

```bash
git branch <user>/<slug>/<id>-<issue-slug> <user>/<slug>
git worktree add ../<repo>-wt/<id>-<issue-slug> <user>/<slug>/<id>-<issue-slug>
```

Then in **a single message**, spawn one Agent (Task tool) per issue so they run concurrently. Every sub-agent prompt MUST include:

- the literal word **`ultrathink`** to request deeper reasoning
- working directory: the worktree path
- "follow the `bender-implement-issue` skill for `{slug}#{id}`"
- "be **idiomatic** to the language and framework of the modules touched — apply the relevant language skills (e.g. `golang-pro`, `typescript-advanced-types`, `best-practices-svelte5`, `rust-best-practices`)"
- "commit on the assigned branch only — do **not** push, do **not** open a PR; the parent integrates and opens one combined PR"

Wait for every sub-agent to complete. Then on the main checkout:

```bash
git checkout <user>/<slug>
git merge --no-ff <issue-branch>   # for each completed branch, dependency-stable order
```

Re-run lint and the test suite on the integration branch after the merges land. Resolve conflicts by issue intent.

If a sub-agent failed (tests red, blocked, surfaced a problem): mark that issue `status: blocked` with the reason in `notes`, leave its branch un-merged, continue with the rest.

Clean up worktrees:

```bash
git worktree remove ../<repo>-wt/<id>-<issue-slug>   # each merged or abandoned worktree
git worktree prune
```

Verify with `git worktree list` that only the main worktree remains.

#### Sequential (single ready issue, or none parallelizable)

Invoke `bender-implement-issue` directly on the integration branch. Same constraints — idiomatic, no per-issue PR; the parent opens the combined PR.

#### HITL / Blocked

- **HITL**: stop, explain the specific decision or input needed, wait for the user.
- **Blocked**: set `status: blocked`, record the reason in `notes`, move on. Once the blocker clears, set `status: todo` before resuming.

### 5. Loop

After the batch integrates, return to §3. Newly-completed issues unblock downstream work. Stop when `{{.commands.next}} {slug}` reports `all_done: true` or only HITL/blocked remain.

### 6. Open the combined PR

```bash
git push -u origin <user>/<slug>
```

Open one PR off `<user>/<slug>` to the default branch. Title: the PRD title. Body:

- one bullet per issue (id, title, key acceptance)
- aggregated test plan from each issue's verification

### 7. Status report

Use `{{.commands.context}} {slug}` to get current issue counts per track.

```text
PRD: <project name>
Done:        <count>
In Review:   <count>
Blocked:     <count> (<issue IDs>)
QA:          <count>
Remaining:   <count> (<issue list>)
Points done: <sum> / <total>
PR:          <integration PR URL>

Track coverage:
{{range .tracks}}
  {{.}}:     <done>/<total>
{{end}}
```

Update `prd.yaml` status to `complete` when all issues are done.
